lists.text: Doesn't mean I don't have or share strong opinions on what the best ways to use it are. But I don't pass my opinions off as accepted fact.
I think you the reader deserve to know all of JS, how it works inside and out, so you can make your own informed judgements.
This is as tragic as it is disrespectful/condescending. Every time I read/hear, "I always tell devs..." followed by such advice, I cringe.
So many books (and bloggers and other thoughtleaders) long-ago decided developers can't be trusted w/ all of JS, so they need to be guided.
The thing I did differently w/ @YDKJS compared to many previous books on JS is... I trusted the reader to be able to handle all of JS.
Quickest way to ensure someone disagrees w/ you is to tweet it out. Slowest way is to write a book. But they'll disagree nonetheless.
